text:
cardboard and impenetrable packing tape,
an aching back and head as the clock makes its rounds,
my morning adrenaline a faint whisper.
but books...
my joy combats my wistfulness as they agree to a momentary standstill.
do they know?
do they know what grace brought them this far?
do they know of those who would pay in blood for a full class schedule, food in the pantry and a safe home?
some must. 
snap.
staple.
stamp.
the girls titter around me not knowing my heart goes with each package.
not knowing my dreams are stronger than this spindle frame.
snap.
staple.
stamp.
i'm coming.
these years of exhaustion and ambiguity will not be for nothing.
the pace i maintained that left my body and spirit nearly indiscernible will be a thing of the past.
i suppose it's less of a boast and more of a vow.
a vow that honors structure of my mind and the obdurance of my hands.
no one ever told me i'd ever be something beyond an honest day's work and a clever quip.
there is a beauty in that life that's far more poignant than the garish faces our culture demands we idolize.
but, when my heart started beating i had the uncomfortable realization that it wouldn't settle for a life of quiet heroism.
snap.
staple. 
stamp.
one day you will turn around, and i will have taken the world by storm; they will know my story.
a story that is just as much a commentary on hope as it is pain.
i just can't skip this chapter.

text:
males get rapped too. yes its a true reality and i bet many of you know. but do you know that males can get rapped by their male counter parts???
this too happens. alot of us were not happy when #metoo movement was used for wring purposes but along came the truth of many monstrous faces. while i agree that some men are trash and that they are worse than dogs even...but some also are their going through worse than we can imagine.
but the taboo of being called gay , being called absurd names stop men from coming forward. women arw used to it , they have been called names , abused and what not from the start of time but men? they have been in the privileged catagory so if something does happen to them , they hide it. not even telling their closest friends because
people will call them gay , even if they are not.
people will not believe them
people will call them weak 
their masculinity will be frowned upon
their masculinity will be challenged.
these and many more things stop them from coming forward with their #metoo.
but i just wanna say that it doesn't matter, getting rapped is not your fault , and it does not affect your masculinity or prove you gay if you are not. 
what i'm trying to say is that if a girl has soo much to go through when she reveals that she has been wronged , imagine a guys saying that he is been wronged by a woman , of more power or a man , just imagine the chaos it would create around him.
and that's what i want to change. equality is when both genders have equal peace of mind and ways of expressing themselves without being called names or abused for exposing the wrong doer. 
i hope everyone stays safe and that rappists should be stoned to faintness , woken up , treated , than stoned on their injuries, than treated and than burned alive in a most painful way imagineable. . 
drop a comment if you agree.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
dianggap sepele padahal penting (banget)
.
di indonesia bentuk catcalling terjadi dimana saja, kejadian catcalling ini entah di jalanan, lingkungan sekolah, lingkuhan kerja, taman, dan juga tempat-tempat lainnya yang kadang tidak mengenal waktu terjadinya. namun masih sangat banyak orang-orang menggangap catcalling adalah kegiatan iseng dan sepele, padahal pengaruhnya besar. bisa saja si korban takut untuk keluar dan bersosialisasi karena adanya catcalling yang ditujukan ke dia sebelumnya. selain itu, apabila melaporkan kejadian ini korban dapat disangka overreacting karena masalah yang sepele.
.
mari sama-sama lebih aware dengan catcalling, apabila orang lain yang menjadi korban, dapat menegur pelakunya dan segera laporkan segala bentuk tindakan kekerasan seksual apabila anda atau orang disekeliling anda mengalaminya.
.

text:
‚Äúbeing born a woman is my awful tragedy,‚Äù sylvia plath wrote in her journal in 1952. ‚Äúmy interest in men and their lives is often misconstrued as a desire to seduce them, or as an invitation to intimacy. my consuming desire to mingle with road crews, sailors and soldiers, barroom regulars ‚Äî to be part of a scene, anonymous, listening, recording ‚Äî all is spoilt by the fact that i am a girl, a female always in danger of assault and battery. yet, god, i want to be able to sleep in an open field, to travel west, to walk freely at night.‚Äù
. 
i keep sylvia with me, her restlessness, her joyfully sleazy feminine desire, her impatience with good behaviour; i keep it under my pillow, in my bag, on my desk, close to my body always. sylvia knew how to live in the world, she knew how to really rage at all the things that were denied to her female body. what i treasure most about her is her deep hunger for the space around her, for physical environments that were unfamiliar, uncomfortable, wildly different from those she already knew. my heart breaks for this unfulfilled desire of hers, and when i walk around my own city late at night, when i slip into places where i should not be, i bring her with me, and i make promises to her and to myself that i will not let this hunger for freedom flicker or wane.
. 
i keep her with me especially during one of the most common conversations i find myself a part of when discussing places with my girlfriends ‚Äî neighbourhoods to find flats in, clubs to visit, new sights to see. ‚Äúis it safe?‚Äù we always ask, impulsively. an important question, of course, but also an incomplete one.

source: thehinduread

text:
women from all walks of life are silenced, stifled and ignored. 
they're often lead to believe, from an early age in life, that they "can't", aren't good enough, have no value or worth and that they should be seen rather than heard.

even now, as #metoo gives women an opportunity to stand with their sisters and fellow survivors, we are often shushed. shamed. pushed aside.

it's time to take back our voices. 
it's time to raise each other up.
it's time to stomp and roar and be heard! 
join me in this movement. 
lend me your voice so other women stop fearing theirs! 
#womenempowerment #womensmarch #girlgang #bosswoman #bossbabe #she #womenauthors #womenwriters #beseenbeheard #raiseherup #metoo #yourbodyyourchoice

text:
oklahoma women's march 2019 
this is why i march: 
i march because i stand against injustice towards women and minorities. i march because our government and society are such that rapists are regularly acquitted, women are constantly demeaned, objectified, threatened, and assaulted, and a person who has done these things can be elected president or put on the supreme court. i march because toxic masculinity exists, and because a woman who speaks "out of line" can be systematically flooded with rape and death threats and her job and livelihood destroyed. i march because women's health is still all too often not taken seriously and because women are not listened to enough. i march because equality is still a long way away.
i march because these problems are so much worse for women of color and other minorities. i march because nazis and white supremacists are getting bolder, countless families have been separated at the border, black people continue to be profiled and murdered at horrific rates, native voices continue to be ignored and treaties broken, native women continue to disappear and suffer astronomical amounts of assault, trans people continue to be murdered, lgbtq+ people continue to be kicked out of their homes, jewish and muslim people continue to be targeted for their religion and ethnicity, and much, much more. i‚Äôm marching because of #metoo and the harassment and discrimination i‚Äôve faced, but i‚Äôm especially marching to stand with all of my sisters of color, lgbtq+, disabled, and immigrant sisters, who face so much more discrimination and threats than i do, on a daily basis. theirs are the voices that must be elevated the most and it was a joy to see that happen today and to participate in this massive call for change.

#womenswave #wmok2019 #awomansplaceisintheresistance #resist #dissent #ruthbaderginsburg #princessleia

------
as a survivor of domestic violence, sexual harassment and yes; sexual assault, i was moved by the recent gillette commercial. 
years ago, when i worried my son might someday adopt the ways of a family culture with a history of domestic violence, i moved him far away from it at a very young age. the scars of what had happened to me never went away (they only faded). when i experienced sexual harassment and assault again, the emotional wounds were once again exposed. 
it took years, no .... it took decades to get to the point of being ready to risk judgement and ridicule and share my experiences. 
unfortunately, i've found that while the #metoo  and #timesup movements have brought #awareness and even changed some laws.  for the average female (or male), getting support and belief after sharing such a painful and shameful experience seems to only bring real support when it‚Äôs a near death situation or when it involves a high profile individual.  most people are initially empathetic then become uncomfortable and and slowly fade away as if you have leprosy or something.

we can move on from such experiences but the consequences from it are life changing. so while others see the ‚Äòwe believe‚Äù gillette commercial as controversial, i was brought to tears by it and appreciate gillette's change in perspective.  #thankyougillette #webelieve #thankyou #gillette #thebestamancanget

text:
i watched the @gillette ad that everyone has been talking about lately. many men are outraged, and getting very defensive. the #metoo movement, feminist movements and equality movements are doing better than they have before in 2019 and that's a huge plus.

but why are men becoming this defensive over the ad and why are they acting like their masculinity is being stripped away from them like gillette has just released an ad about a new nut slicing razor. 
for a lot of men, their entire lives are built off of father expectation, peer expectation, societal norms and is all very superficial. so it doesn't surprise me when men in the masses become defensive over an ad.. their egos. key word: ego. ego should have nothing to do with masculinity but unfortunately it does, it's called toxic masculinity. 
in no way did the ad attack masculinity, it attacked toxic masculinity. and man to man, if you were negatively impacted by this ad, i am not here to push you down in anyway, but to say i understand, i'm on your side and we have to work together in re-shaping what real masculinity means to the world in 2019 for everyone.

text:
@officialkenbarbie
the interview is from 2002. 
nas‚Äô stillmatic dropped at the tail end of 2001, and he delivered the most talked about record for the next several years. ‚Äúether‚Äù is regarded by many as the best hip-hop diss song of all time. rappers began to use the term ‚Äúethered‚Äù to describe how they would annihilate enemies, further solidifying the legendary status of the track. months after the album dropped, nas did an interview with wendy williams that has only just resurfaced. wasit deep in the beef with jigga, nas lashes out at his nemesis by calling him out for associating with r. kelly.

lifetime‚Äôs surviving r. kelly six-part docu-series reexamined the history of r. kelly‚Äôs alleged sexual misconduct, but they failed to grab this key sound clip from the nas interview. ‚Äúi don‚Äôt put out no movies, that‚Äôs not my style,‚Äù nas stated on williams‚Äô old radio show on new york‚Äôs wbls. it appears that nas was referencing jay-z‚Äôs move of making visuals to take shots at mobb deep and others at summer jam in 2001. ‚Äúi could have shown the r. kelly video that everybody‚Äôs talking about, made fun of it and shown jay hanging out. when jay and them was in there doing best of both worlds, you can‚Äôt tell me jay didn‚Äôt see a 14-year-old girl come in the studio and sit on r. kelly‚Äôs lap. you gonna sit here and tell me, that working on that album, he ain‚Äôt never see no 14-year-old girl come in the vicinity?‚Äù ‚Äúyou‚Äôve seen it go down,‚Äù nas continued. ‚Äúi‚Äôve been around r. kelly ‚Ä¶ i‚Äôve been on tour with him, it didn‚Äôt last too long. but i been around him. i didn‚Äôt see no 14-year-old, but i talked to the man and i seen there‚Äôs a little problem there. the brother needs help and i pray for him. but if i sit here and did an album about women with him, i‚Äôm definitely maybe indulging in‚Ä¶ he had to be indulging in some 14-year-olds. ‚Äù

text:
think about it!

seems to be a few ppl out there under the belief that masculinity and ‚Äòmanhood‚Äô is being attacked. i‚Äôve seen the word ‚Äòsnowflake‚Äô thrown around a lot, in response to the gillette ad for instance. the boys will be boys attitude has been totally abused, and is dangerous in the hands of those who think fighting it out & making crude remarks is what differentiates men from ‚Äòsnowflakes‚Äô. there isn‚Äôt anything more honourable than a man who doesn‚Äôt have to resort to his fists or derogatory comments to communicate. being emotionally manipulative or physically violent was never the definition of masculinity. those who open their eyes will see what the ad & associated movements are targeting which is a change in attitude & a better sense on acceptable behaviour. those who take this as a personal attack on their ‚Äòmanhood‚Äô are insecure, & are perpetuating misconceptions which actually contradict the very definition of masculinity they so badly want to protect. perhaps this is above some intellects. perhaps some ppl are scared of change. perhaps some ppl are cowards & have to puff their chest to compensate everything they lack on the inside. perhaps those ppl should ask themselves if they had a daughter or son who was beaten up, harassed or bullied in some way, would they take that perpetrator out for a drink, shake their hand & ask for all the details about it so they could relish & boast about how manly it made them? if not then welcome sir, welcome to the world of double standards you so adamantly wish to float in. have a nice stay & i sincerely hope it doesn‚Äôt backfire should whatever behaviour you condone impacts any of your personal relationships one day.

take your insecurities away, stop personalising things & making this about you. it‚Äôs about invoking change where it is needed & recognising when you‚Äôre getting it right. this applies to everyone. just think about it! 
#change #timeforachange #masculine #toxicpeople #boyswillbeboys #metoo

text:
pics from a trip to the edgar cayce center , and coralla island nc. 
some much goodness in it. üíñthis was one more big step in my healing journey.

i drove alone with my 3yr old daughter .

i was terrified of driving in the mountains because of ptsd.

mountains were a trigger for me.

but i was going to get from iowa to the other side of that mountian.

i knew that beach was waiting. those wild horses.

so i dug in and faced my fear.

my little girl was the most untoddler like ,space holding angel.

she came to see me conquer. 
and so i did.üíñ i made my peace with the mountains.  i got back a piece of my 12yrold self .

and every time i am willing i get to live my dream.

i don't really care all that much about money or this and that .

but i do care greatly,  that if you learn one thing from me that is this. üî•you are your greatest teacher üî•you can do anything and everything your afraid of.
üî•you are more powerful and divinely supported then most people will have you believing . üî•even if it hurts , your scared and you feel like it will break you it wont.

face your fears , go to the parts of you that are scattered and reclaim them. üíñmost of all stay alone , avoid large groups , and avoid anything that smells like pure spiritual fuckery. if it smells like shit it's shit.

i don't care how pretty the package is. 
be a eagle , not a pigeon üíñ

text:
today a durham bestie @jourdanfairchild invited me last minute to see the one and only tarana burke (@taranajaneen) speak at duke for #mlkday. i‚Äôd planned to sit in front of the computer, working for hours like i‚Äôve been doing every weekend to get ready for the @thedoubleshift launch. i‚Äôve been saying no to a lot of things lately... party invites, requests for calls and meetings, and even time with my kid. but when the founder of the #metoo movement is speaking two miles from my house, i had to say yes.

her talk was like kindling for my embers that have to burn 24/7 as i get ready for the most important project of my life. the work i do to empower mothers would not exist in nearly same way without tarana. she is a profound intellectual influence on everything i do.
her speech was wonderful, and one line that sticks with me is ‚Äúif you are truly a visionary, people will look at like you like you a crazy.‚Äù i have gotten more than a few dismissals, yawns, and eye rolls about the work i have come to understand is my calling. i hope my work to tell intersectional stories about what mothers face continues in her legacy and vision.

#momstoo #taranaburke #dukemlk #feminism #feminist #activism

text: i'm so humbled by the ladies who have reached out to me looking for a healthier, more fulfilling life. these brave women have kindly shared their stories, their pain points, and their aspirations and i couldn't be more proud of them for acknowledging where they are at and knowing they deserve better.  i am excited to share the same tools with them that helped me get through all of my pain. if you're frustrated or downright defeated feeling about a lack of vulnerability, increased anxiety/triggers, self deprecating mindchatter, self confidence issues, and more, schedule a free 1 hour call with me this week to learn about my program and customize a helping plan for you. i'm here to help üíú

text:
give yourself time.
the healing process was slow. make sure you schedule in self love time whatever that means to you.

life is a continual journey. there is never a time when you'll be "fixed" because while it may have felt like it you were never broken. you had experiences, which moved your life path down a different journey.

still, give yourself time to be ready to take on the world.

text:
yeaaaaaaaaaah!
we are back officially. üíÉüíÉüíÉ
i truly really missed the girls these four sundays.

today we had our first meeting for the year. our reference read 16/20/1/2019. the first figure stood for the number of times we have met since the academic year began, while the rest represented the days date.

before our chairperson for the day, captured in picture 2, would take up full responsibility for the the day, i made the girls share how their holiday went. nothing was stricking. not even that they had a psycher. üôÑüòäby heaven, these group of girls are contesting hard for the most boring group i have ever facilitatedü§£üòÇüòÇ
.
.
.
.
usually, we draw lessons from experiences shared. we apply critical consciousness to every single detail in a shared experience replicating inferences and bring core values to the fore, allowing participants the opportunity to decide what they would rather have their personal narratives to read.

violet nwaneri and myself shared too. i was lagos for a week. i was the most memorable one for me. vayo lost two fair weather friends and made exact same number of friends in the course of the holiday. chai! i'm looking for friends o!ü§£üòãüòÅ .
.
.
.
i had an early evening engagement and had to leave 35 minutes earlier. however, vayo continued in my absence. she had lesson notes on vision and goal setting. while i missed out taking shots of the notes, there is a sneak peek of one of the flip charts in the second shot that has our chairperson of the day in it. 
while i missed the timing of my early evening engagement/responsibility by one minute courtesy of a vehicle packed at the entry of the venue, i was still giving a shot to carry on with the responsibility. 
sunday evening went well.... #gpicalabar #personalchronicles #ekeelim #journaling #volunteering #advocacy #metoo

text: ‚Äúthis dress is a thrift store find and quite dear to me,‚Äù says taylor, 23, a new york-based writer & editor. ‚Äúit reminds me of something an old movie star might have worn. i want to wear it in public but never have. i was #dresscoded in high school, and the school forced me to cover up my body in xl drabby gym clothes. the shame of having to walk through the halls in those clothes was something that felt exclusively female, and it was an excuse for the boys to point and laugh at me. as you grow up, it doesn‚Äôt get any better. instead of teachers looking at your body and judging, you deal with men who think they are entitled to women‚Äôs bodies the moment any part is exposed. if i wore this dress, with its lace bodice and see-through fabric, i know i would be slut-shamed verbally or even assaulted physically by countless men on the streets. so instead of wearing this beautiful dress, i longingly look at it hanging in my closet.‚Äù @taylorspicee *** have you been #dresscoded or experienced #slutshaming because of your clothing? message or email me (leoratan@yahoo.com) if you want to participate in this project. ** for more information, click on link in bio. *** #beingdresscoded #slutbashing #everydaysexism #schooldresscode #dresscode #stoprape #rapeculture #metoo

if you say to your female employees "i hate to see you go, but love to watch you leave."
*
take a picture of your employees cleavage and then send it to the boss.
*
think your female co-worker wants a dildo as a gift and wants to fuck you just because they are kind to you.
*
if you don't want assistance from a female service advisor, simply because she's female.
*
being called a "skirt".
*
if you're offended by a commercial that is calling out shitty "men", think about anyone of those comments being directed at your daughter. what's more offensive?

text:
@katiehorwitch recently asked me on the @womenagainstnegativetalk podcast to finish the statement: ‚Äúi wish that more women...?‚Äù my response...‚Äùlived in their softness.‚Äù
.
4 years ago i got this tattoo on my wrist. it reads ‚Äúinfragilis et tenera‚Äù which in latin translates to...
unbreakable/strong and tender.
.
as i explained to katie, women are taught to take up little space. in fighting against that, we feel that we need to get loud, tough, and overcompensate. when i got this tattoo i was exiting a season of ‚Äútoughness.‚Äù i had experienced some hard shit, hard shit that subsequently made me hard. i fell into the mentality of ‚Äúwhat doesn‚Äôt kill you makes you stronger.‚Äù but i soon realized that what doesn‚Äôt kill you also makes you softer.
.
so i got this tattoo as a reminder that life is hard, but it doesn‚Äôt have to make me hard. i feel like my best self when i‚Äôm living in the softness, when i‚Äôm showing up with love, compassion, empathy and vulnerability‚Äîfor myself and others. this is what makes us strong. this is what makes us unbreakable.

text:
aviation: this is what it‚Äôs like to fly (1/10) by nicholas jones, 01 january 2019. -

when peace does take the place of pain,
and when hope does fall instead of rain,
and when love is no longer made in vain,
this is what it‚Äôs like to fly - this is what it‚Äôs like to fly,

when taking the leap and daring to dream,
and when the world is no longer as it once seemed,
and when taking back control of your own destiny,
this is what it‚Äôs like to fly - this is what it‚Äôs like to fly,

when your faith is tried and tested true,
and when it seems as if you can‚Äôt pull through,
and when then somehow - you‚Äôre still able to,
this is what it‚Äôs like to fly - this is what it‚Äôs like to fly,

when you‚Äôre looking up to the lord above,
and when feeling his most gracious love,
and when there‚Äôs so much to be afraid of,
this is what it‚Äôs like to fly - this is what it‚Äôs like to fly,

when your anxiety peaks and you‚Äôre feeling weak,
and when you have all of the words but you just can‚Äôt speak,
and when you keep on moving to spite defeat,
this is what it‚Äôs like fly - this is what it‚Äôs like to fly,

and so do not fear the concept of aviation,
when you have not reached your destination,
because taking flight is just the manifestation,
of your greatest desires in the face of adversity,

this is what it‚Äôs like to fly - this is what it‚Äôs like to fly. -

text:
january 20th, 2019: sexual victims endure a lot but it's invisible

imagine not being able to go to a place, a place you used to love, a place that gave you joy simply because it is tied to someone that sexually assaulted you. imagine feeling physically sick because someone, a stranger, someone you do not know, have never met, ever, just happens to put on the same cologne as the one an attacker wore. imagine not being able to stand a certain nickname you used to adore because of the memories the nickname evokes. many, millions of people experience that daily and you can't see it. it's great that #metoo happened but we have to do more, a lot more.¬†#myblackoutpoems¬†@centreforarttapes

yup. 21-38. art school girl photo student playing dress up in her bathtub to the basic graphic designer who just spent her day making free people returns, eating brunch, and setting her crystals out to charge in the full moon üòÇ although i‚Äôm way less edgy and my color pallet is less grabby these days i feel way more comfortable in my skin and i have way less fucks to give the rest of the world. it‚Äôs been a rough road, but i‚Äôve made some good headway. 
i always loved the ‚Äúred dress‚Äù pic because it was part of my self-exploration process. this one was actually part of a series of self portraits which dealt with trying to figure out my way in a world very much built for men and with the repercussions of sexual assault. i‚Äôm sure a lot of you can identify with the battered and bruised girl smoking a cigarette in a frumpy red prom dress. ü§ó me too, my loves. #metoo. üí™

text:
#womensmarch 2019 #montreal. a few brave ones showed up to represent at the almost - 30 degree celcius. #deepfreeze star and i's 3rd march!!! we continue the road to justice and equality. we continue to speak for those who are unable to. 
we must speak from a place of awareness, healing and be able to speak safely.
bravo to the true heroes and sheroes who help, heal, speak out, inspire every day!  the #metoo mouvement is only the beginning, so much yet to be done.

as i am battling a very bad cold, i could not follow along with the rest of the event. 
i was able to get through an interview with a cbc reporter  but what really got me emotional, i was interviewed by..... i would never have imagined that a " friend" of the sociopath ex would request an interview for the concordian( concordia university paper) . she pretended well to not know who i was( having documented all would prove otherwise) but i was straight forward with her on who i was and what he is and that  i am far from being the only victim/survivor of his abuse, manipulation and violence. what happens next who knows!! we continue to do what our given purpose demands. #warrioroflight #1billionrising  #rise #resist #unite #untiltheviolencestops #rape ##domesticviolence #narcissist #sociopath #abuse #survivor
name: Sonja Matschuck

text: perhaps ones of my favorite paintings of all time. gruesome? sure, but once you know the both the story of judith and holofernes (the narrative for this painting) and the actual story of the artist, artemisia gentileschi, it is empowering as a woman. the same issues addressed in the old testament story and in the 1600‚Äôs are the same issues women are still trying to make heard. so go ahead and pout about #gillette showing us that men can do better. ‚Äúgentileschi was as self-made and as independent as was conceivable in her time‚Äîand she fought hard for it. ‚Äúyou will find the spirit of caesar in this soul of a woman,‚Äù she once wrote of herself in a letter to a patron. in several instances, she freed herself from shackles that had been placed on her (whether literally or figuratively) by men. most famously, she won a rape trial she brought against her teacher, the elder artist agostino tassi, in an era when women‚Äôs claims were rarely believed over those of their male counterparts. a very public and controversial trial ensued, in which gentileschi was forced to describe her assault in detail. during the trial, she was subjected to sibille, a process in which ropes were tied to her fingers and tightened progressively. the practice was meant to determine whether or not she was telling the truth. after seven months in court, the judged finally ruled in gentileschi‚Äôs favor. tassi was sentenced to five years in prison, but never actually served time. soon after the trial, gentileschi moved to florence and set up her own studio‚Äîaway from her father. it was around this time that she began a series of five works depicting the old testament story of judith and holofernes, in which a woman plots to kill a warlord who‚Äôs besieged her town. under the cover of night, judith is successful in beheading him.‚Äù #artemesiagentileschi #judithslayingholofernes #metoo #thebestamancanget #arthistory #listentowomen #keepitup #badasswomen

text:
this is the result of 9 months in the making. really, it is a result of a lifetime of listening and seeking to understand myself, seeking to improve myself, to be a better partner and ultimately, to be a better man. 
last april, i was inspired to write the book "man school: relating with women in the #metoo era." it took 2 months to write, deliver and produce a #1 new release on amazon that changed the trajectory of my career and has already made the difference for hundreds of people. 
after working with francesca fiorentini and kate elston on a piece for aj+, i decided to create an online course that goes deeper into what is possible for the modern man. this was back in october.

and today, i am so filled with the pleasant exhaustion of having completed something that comes from my soul..."man school: the online course" is here, is live and is now available. 
this is an online, home-study course for men who want to live better lives, have better relationships and develop themselves as powerful, purpose-driven men. 
7 modules, 2 bonus modules, audio recordings and a total of 31 videos...i am happy.

if you are a man reading this who is looking for something more, something deeper and more-fulfilling, i invite you to click this link in the bio and take the course:

if you are a woman reading this who loves men, sees our potential and knows the depth we can bring...share this with those men.

thank you. i love you. i am always standing for your greatness. -matthew

text:
this may be weird or sound stupid but the night that i got attacked and raped i was wearing this purse. i have held this purse so close keeping it close to me ripped and ugly looking people must've thought what an ugly purse. i would wear it and i would keep it near my bed... yesterday as i looked at it i cried, and held it close to me... i figured it was time to let go... so today i burned it along with everything i attached myself with it... next is the clothes i wore.
#metoo 
#imalittlebitstronger 
#imasurvivor 
#startingover

i feel like we need some beauty today. the world can be an ugly place and we need to consider whether we contribute to that or work to make it better. truth is such a complex issue. sometimes we think it will make us feel better, and other times we let our emotions overrule and write our own narrative because the grief is to much.
whatever the truth, the one that is in the middle, i hope the skating community can come together to heal and to promote the change it so desperately needs. 
and if you are struggling please know there is help. there are people who love you and want to help you. please, let them. please reach out. i know it is scary but your life does matter. 
and don‚Äôt be afraid to ask someone how they are doing. even if they are smiling and asking you never know what is going on behind that mask. ask. reach out. let‚Äôs support and spread love.

text:
my extra goodies.. .
what i bring to the practice of sexology that is unique..
.
üôèüèºmy background as a registered nurse for three decades in many capacities has given me a unique perspective on health, illness & humanity; including our relationships and sexuality. .
üôèüèº add to that my twenty-four year yoga journey. .
üôèüèº i kicked the spice up a notch while writing a sex and relationship column and hosting my own weekly radio talk show for the past decade. .
üôèüèº my private life is my greatest teacher being a #metoo survivor, mother of three & grandmother of four granddaughters, all giving me a special connection to womankind, making me a fierce advocate for equal and fair treatment of women and men. .
üôèüèºto balance my fierce feminist side is my life soul traveler, my husband mark. for over 30 years he has influenced me with his powerful, compassionate, loving, kind, respectful and sensitive, confident masculinity.  he also happens to be a feminist/humanist. he reminds me to seek the best in myself and to measure my professional successes one person at a time, which is where my purpose blooms. .
üôèüèº merge all of this together and you get me.  my yin/yang concepts that bring east/west philosophy, medicine, psychology and spirituality (without any religious intonation) into my work, life and personal exploration.  what you see is what you get - honest, to the point, full of love, yet intolerant of mistreatment of anyone, including myself.  i will always tell you like i see it - and leave you to decide how or if you put that to personal use.  no judgement.  no shame.  only love.
.
üôèüèºall counseling appointments are conducted via skype or zoom. http://drnsp.com/making-an-appointment/
.
üôèüèº
#drnancysuttonpierce #clinicalsexologist #doctorofhumansexuality #liveyourfinestlife #sexualhealing #empoweredwomenempowerwomen  #consciouslivingsexuality #consciouslivingsexualityshow

text:
if you saw my stories earlier this week, you will know i had a rather grim experience with an ‚Äòexhibitionist.‚Äô an exhibitionist is someone who indecently exposes themselves to a non-consenting person. basically, a man who likes to get his willy out to wank in public or c.k louis.

it seems like a too nicer term for what it is doesn‚Äôt it? like i got a vip invite to an exclusive art preview in a high class gallery, rather than being sexually harassed while i eat a cheese sandwich in my campervan by a guy who looked like he could have been an accountant or a lawyer.

dick. wanker. prick. all seem like better words to describe it, but hey, i guess that‚Äôs hard to write in academic or medical journals. ü§∑üèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è i won‚Äôt lie, it made me lose my place a bit. ever had that when you‚Äôre reading out loud but the words start to jump around, so you lose your place, and a deafening silence envelopes the room while you frantically find your place again. yeah? that.

i did what i had to do. walked, read, watched movies, made friends, drank lots of gin, moaned about brexit, to get back to where i was before. it worked. i‚Äôm back.

don‚Äôt worry, i will write a blog about it all soon enough and i‚Äôve already written the chapter for my book. i‚Äôve called it ‚Äòthe wanker.‚Äô üçÜüí¶

it seems like a too nicer term for what it is doesn‚Äôt it? like i got a vip invite to an exclusive art preview in a high class gallery, rather than being sexually harassed while i eat a cheese sandwich in my campervan by a guy who looked like he could have been an accountant or a lawyer.

text:
yesterday, i was at washington dc to join the women's march. i unfortunately didn't take many pictures, but it was stunning. the amount of people there of old and young ages flabbergasted me. 
it made me feel so empowered, people chanting things like "my body, my right!" or just various chants about justice and domcracy.

though, the amount of jokes abput trump was funny- it did make me feel sad. i would've liked to see more meaningful signs about pro choice, #metoo , black lives, and such instead of a joke. it was kinda like a sea of youtube comments at times, which was saddening.

overall, absolutely beautiful and empowering and i'm so glad i had a chance to attend. i also got to see my first bit of snow ever!

text:
‚Äúi am within you 
everywhere, i am
swimming in your veins 
i am in your, heart, 
when it starts to beat
and i will cradle your remains
i will hold you steady, 
when you think you‚Äôre going to fall
wherever you go
whatever you do 
i will be there through it all

wherever you go
whatever you do
i will hold your hand

go on your way
go on, you way
go on
i will hold you
go on
i will hold you.‚Äù
- @jaijagdeesh ~~~ as i sit here rooted,
as the witness of the wounds 
torn open within,
i realise, that before i open my mouth, and my heart, as the lioness, 
i am, i am... i must cradle the bruises,
the shivering, shaking child,

kiss her wounds from the root up,
welcome space 
for her fears to be felt,
to be attended to, until she can eventually, transmute - into the lioness,
to be here with me now.

so we can rise tall, and roar together. 
to the dark weed - your time is up.

text:
-this morning i came across the whole gillette razor commercial debacle. i was astounded by the amount of backlash that the commercial is getting. ‚Äî-for those of you that don‚Äôt know, gillette recently released a commercial that challenged toxic masculinity in a #metoo era. ‚Äî-this commercial is getting more dislikes than likes on the notion that it is attacking masculinity, and demonizing men. ‚Äî-while i can understand how some men could feel that the commercial is calling masculinity bad and blaming all men for the assault on women (physical and non), the idea is to be an invitation for men to feel and show all emotions and use their power to keep each other accountable. by saying ‚Äúboys will be boys‚Äù whenever they do something toxic, it makes the situation worse by not keeping accusers responsible for actions that can have been learned (and can therefore be unlearned) ‚Äî-those that think this is not gillette‚Äôs place aren‚Äôt remembering that the company sells razors for shaving. shaving is a highly ritualistic act done by most men when they hit puberty. a ‚Äúmasculine‚Äù act. so why does the company not have the right to speak up?! what are your thoughts on the matter? -
-

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
yesterday we joined 250k angelenos in our 3rd annual #womensmarch. here are just a few of the reasons i march. ‚úäüèæ‚úäüèø‚úäüèΩ‚úäüèª üåà ‚ù§Ô∏è i march for myself, for future generations of women, and for the strong women that came before me. i march because i‚Äôve been spoken over in meetings and conversations at work. i‚Äôve had my great ideas ignored entirely. along with fellow female colleagues, i‚Äôve been excluded from opportunities with leadership simply because of our gender. i‚Äôve heard the #metoo movement used as a punchline.

i‚Äôve been promoted for a role and learned after the fact they paid me less than the white female with less experience before me. i march for intersectionality. because women earn only 80 cents for every dollar a man earns in the same role. i march because the wage disparity worsens when you introduce race. i walk because as a woman of color, that number drops to 67 cents for a black woman, and only 62 cents for a hispanic women for a mans earned $1. i march because poverty is sexist.

i march for all the times i‚Äôve been harassed by men, in daylight, in a parking lot, at a grocery store, pretending to have been ‚Äúflattered, but uninterested‚Äù to ensure my personal safety, and the safety of his fragile male ego was preserved. 
i march because some people still support r kelly. because people still think christine blasey ford was lying. because there are men (and women) out there who are actually angry because a gillette razor ad challenged men to be be better.

i march to celebrate the blue wave, the historic 117 women elected to congress; the most diverse in our country‚Äôs #herstory. i march because we aren‚Äôt finished yet, we‚Äôre just getting started. i march for the comaraderie, the positivity, the good energy, the inclusivity. i march to build bridges, not walls. 
i march because you should ‚Äúnever doubt that a small group of thoughtful, committed citizens can change the world; indeed, it's the only thing that ever has.‚Äù
#womensmarch #womensmarchla #timesup

text:
thank you @daily_bibleverses for this beautiful reminder in times of hardship.

the power of prayer will bring you answers to the many questions that you have regarding the uncertainties with your life situation. it will help you heal and forgive. it will help you realize, that you as a person, deserve to be respected, feel safe and valued.

it is important for survivors of domestic abuse to help others, as this can help turn their negative experiences into something positive. this will help you recognize the full extent of your partner's abusive behavior. this will surround you with practical¬†and emotional support from other women in refuge.

prayer in times of hardship will help you realize that you do not need to be a victim, and that you have an opportunity to stop being a victim. the power is within yourself. the power is within your prayer. @aaddaagirl

text: it was the #womensmarch2019 today. i feel passionately about equality in all its forms, especially women‚Äôs equality. this is not about my rights, it‚Äôs about our rights - all women. the ones who are not allowed to decide for themselves if and how many kids they want, the ones whose lives are dominated by men, the ones who do not get paid the same as men doing the same jobs with exactly the same education, the ones who are not allowed to drive, the ones who are not allowed to get an education, the ones who are not allowed to choose who they want to love and so on. being polite about these demands is no longer an option (was it ever? are we always impolite when we ask something that makes other people uncomfortable?). so i agree with this lady, fuck #patriarchy - we need to challenge this in all its forms. it doesn‚Äôt serve us, it doesn‚Äôt serve the world. #timesup #metoo #feminism #equality #samerights #ichooseyouchoose #fuckpatriarchy

text:
dear little lynz,
i'm sorry for the things you have gone through, witnessed, and carried with you at such a young age. i'm sorry no one was there for you when you needed it most. to catch those tears, to help you ease fears when you had them. i'm sorry no one was there to protect you from bad things. i'm sorry no one was there to hug you, show you love, or to help you heal and shine like the little ray of sunshine that you are. but i am here now, you are loved, valued, and most of all no one will ever do you any harm to you my inner child. your have suffered enough. it is time to heal and be that happy little girl you deserve to be. i will forever give you the love and support you need. i love you. 
sincerely 
me .

text:
a lot of us were raised to do as we were told. 
no ifs no buts. 
just because someone said so. but i think that time is now gone.
it‚Äôs the time of little people who will grow up to be liberated, free-thinking individuals. 
case in point: i was told by my very opinionated kid today that she doesn‚Äôt like me. my crime? i made her take a shower.
anyhow, her words evoked all sense of anger. how could she? i do everything for her! i‚Äôm so exhausted! she‚Äôs misbehaving! 
but then sanity prevailed. and instead of reacting in anger (which i‚Äôm prone to), i told her.... it‚Äôs fine.
you don‚Äôt have to like me. but i love you. and if you feel like you like me again sometime, let me know.
cue some huffs and puffs. a bit of scowling. a little confusion. and then, some softening.
‚Äòok mama, i love you now‚Äô
i expressed my gratitude. and felt a bit of relief.
i could‚Äôve offered her a bribe. i could‚Äôve given her timeout. 
instead, i gave her a choice. 
to love me or to not. 
because she doesn‚Äôt have to. she should only want to.
just like she never has to do anything she doesn‚Äôt want to, now or ever.
she must do it because she chooses to. .
.
.
.
and that is my take on... freedom. .
.
.

the poem, this  happens  with  every  girl : "me - too'' by gurjot s. kaler ,
is a heartfelt tribute to the millions of women in the world who suffer in  silence and are a victim of sexual harassment-cum-exploitation at every stage of their lives. indeed, it is actually a heartrending reality and a matter of grave concern to note that everyday,  innumerable women are raped, molested, eve-teased and sexually assaulted across the globe. 
the tragic truth is that every women has undergone the pain of sexual violence and faced some sort of sexual abuse during their lifetime, either directly or indirectly. 
the question which really begs for an answer is that whenever any kind of sexual crime happens with women, why are we all silent as the members of society ? don't we all have any moral and social responsibility to stand upright and defend our women's honor, prestige and integrity ? 
why do we refuse to raise our voice ? are we also waiting for that one day when our own mothers, sisters, wives and daughters will come home after becoming victims of sexual harassment and say that, "this happened with me-too". do not suffer in silence. raise your voice before it is too late. the world suffers a lot, not because of the violence of bad people but because of the silence of good people. be the change you wish to see in the world. 
the time has come to realize that we must gather the required courage to support, respect and protect our women as well as ensure their safety, security and survival at any cost.  therefore, "me-too'' is not a mere hashtag, its a global movement in support of women and is meant to  inspire them to raise their suppressed voices against all sorts of injustice in society. 
respect her - support her - protect her.

the tragic truth is that every women has undergone the pain of sexual violence and faced some so of sexual abuse during their lifetime, either directly or indirectly. 
the question which really begs for an answer is that whenever any kind of sexual crime happens with women, why are we all silent as the members of society ? do not we all have any moral and social responsibility to stand upright and defend our women's honor, prestige and integrity ? 
why do we refuse to raise our voice ? are we also waiting for that one day when our own mothers, sisters, wives and daughters will come home after becoming victims of sexual harassment and say that, "this happened with me-too". do not suffer in silence. raise your voice before it is too late. the world suffers a lot, not because of the violence of bad people but because of the silence of good people. be the change you wish to see in the world.

respect her - suppo her - protect her.

text:
i‚Äôm katy and sometimes i‚Äôm a jumble of seemingly contradictory things. i love coffee at all hours of the day and i also love sleeping. i love pizza but hate tomatoes. i like to be liked and validated by the people i care about, and i like to share my opinions. and sometimes that last one can be an area of discomfort.
.
.
if you have opinions and share them you will inevitably upset some people.  i have opinions and i use my social media to share them. i also share tongue in cheek things sometimes, although i try to keep an eye on what‚Äôs appropriate and respectful. try but not always succeed since social media takes out tone and context and how can anyone assume to know my heart posture? (you can‚Äôt)
.
.
i hope those i love know i never post anything to be hurtful, or intentionally offensive. however i am not afraid to dip my toe into the water of things we ‚Äúshouldn‚Äôt‚Äù discuss: religion (i‚Äôm a jesus follower and proud christian), #immigration (i‚Äôll never shut up about the atrocities at the border), #feminism (i‚Äôm wary of #metoo, and yes i care about men and boys too!), etc...i have strong opinions and i can have a big mouth. and i like that about me ‚ù£Ô∏è
.
.
i know this and i am okay with it because my father raised me to use my voice.
.
.
so while people and friendships and relationships mean the world to me, i‚Äôm also aware and okay with not have everyone happy with my thoughts all the time. please know this can be super uncomfortable for me, but being silent when something is on my heart is even less comfortable. ‚ô•Ô∏è
.
.
#christian #feminist #advocate

text:
remember your worth. remember your beauty. no matter what the past held, you can overcome. you will bloom again. as a fellow #metoo, for a long while i felt wilted and dead inside. i felt i wasn't worthy of love or affection. but we are. we are so worthy. male or female, you are worthy of love, affection, and respect. don't let the person who did that to you rob you of those things. they don't deserve to still have that control or power. take it back. my abuse went on for almost 3 years. i knew him. he changed one day. i thought if i just loved him more it would change him back. it would stop the sexual abuse. the horrendous abuse. but one day i realized, i want to bloom again, and i can't if i stay in this tainted soil of a relationship. i fought back and left. and you can to. you are strong. you are brave. if you feel trapped, reach out to someone close. reach out and fight. fight for yourself... because you deserve to bloom again... and you can. you will. üå∏üå∏üå∏üíó xoxo

text:
you're not a victim for sharing your story. you are a survivor setting the world on fire with your truth. and you never know who needs your light. your warmth. your raging courage. 
this story needs to be told.

these days i'm opening up publickly about my story. i was attacked and sexually assaulted in my hotel room while i was travelling alone. i tried to seek justice and press charges but i was accused of lying and charged with vandalism in the hotelroom (where i was attacked) and put in prison. i took my broken heart and turned it into art. ü¶Å or my expression - short f√≠lm (i was called islandia) @islandiafilm we are now distributing it and also want to shine a light on the injustice women have to face everyday around the world when they try to seek their rights and speak up.

the film was premiered at @austinfilmfest in oktober. we now want to distribute proberly thats why we decided to start a crowfunding campaign and 20% will go to a fund that helps women to seek justice after violence and abuse. if you want to see the film check out the link in bio. 
https://www.karolinafund.com/project/view/2291

@thorakaritas

text:
i marched mainly for the solidarity of being with other people who are just as angry, fed up, and hungry for justice. i marched to be reminded that, for all the ugliness in the news, love is still powerful and alive. i saw men holding signs that they were marching for their wives and daughters. i saw parents holding signs declaring their love for their lgbt kids, and children holding signs declaring their love for their two moms and two dads. i saw white people holding #blacklivesmatter‚úäüèæ signs and proclaiming their history as descendants of immigrants. 
it was a fantastic weekend- despite having a bad cold and losing my voice (see stories for highlights). flying back to denver tomorrow, if this snowstorm doesn‚Äôt delay my flight.

people who dont think protests and marches dont work numbers don't lie!

text:
your 2019 resolution: keep up with groundbreaking women. how to accomplish it? bookmark the #lhi platform. get to know the stories of women in entertainment, politics, academia, research, tech, and more. 
1: tarana burke [activism]: bronx-born activist and founder of the #metoo movement. 
2: feifei li [technology]: professor of cs @stanford and director of the stanford ai lab. previously chief scientist of ai/ml @googlecloud. 
3: kathryn minshew [entrepreneurship]: ceo and co-founder of the muse (@themuse), a career development platform with over $28 million in funding. 
4: salma hayek [entertainment]: actress and producer, founder of chime for change that aims to spread female empowerment.

text: i‚Äôll get the bad news out of the way: the only thing not to love about ‚Äúthe romanoffs‚Äù is that there could have been just a slightly bigger splash of color. sure, it‚Äôs hard to fit poc into a story about a historic russian/german family whose bloodline has produced some of the most affected citizens all over the world. and yes, these rich and complex stories did showcase some of the most renown actors in show business, a few of them openly gay playing actual gay roles, and diversity in other realms. i know, it was shot on location in several diverse cities. and yes i counted an endless supply of black extras - we‚Äôre almost there. the reason why i complain is because none of the minorities play neutral characters - which is hard to come by in matthew weiner territory, but here was an opportunity to level the playing field and everyone who wasn‚Äôt white was shoved into at least one stereotype. a majority of these movie length episodes were nothing short of breathtaking in execution and moral, so there‚Äôs that. it was an ambitious undertaking to top ‚Äúmad men‚Äù fame and this show does in an unexpectedly subtle way, still not as great as its predecessor - but stunningly entertaining in its own right. the most shocking scene (a throwback to that horrid lawn mower scene we‚Äôll never forget) comes in the best bit with christina hendricks and isabelle huppert duking it out in a film within a film situation that keeps repeating on me over and over again. two other highlights were: amanda peet‚Äôs incredible range (doled out in a very wonderful brunch scene in bergdorf‚Äôs) and the whacky narrative in beefy cory stoll‚Äôs episode. some of the filling (that is one or three) is a little longwinded, but tie together the overall theme nicely. so much of the stories involve adultery, but wholly this is an homage to complex relationships and the fragility of the human spirit. #theromanoffs #madmen #matthewweiner #directing #screenwriting #storytelling #gayactor #lgbtq #transgender #christinahendricks #isabellehuppert #corystoll #dianelane #amandapeet #actors #actorslife #love #relationships #adultery #metoo #russians
